In recognition of her contribution to the promotion, growth and development of the mushroom industry in Nigeria, Babcock University, Ilisan, Ogun State has been awarded the Mushroom Founders’ Award. The award was presented at the 1st National Mushroom Week and Awards organized by the National Mushroom Growers, Processors and Marketers Association of Nigeria (NAM-GP-MAN). The three-day fiesta held recently at the Abuja International Conference Centre attracted stakeholders, captains of industry as well as government representatives like the Hon. Minister of Agriculture and Rural Development, Dr. Mohammad Mahmood Abubakar and the Hon. Minister of Industry, Trade, Prof. Ademola Tayo. Babcock University Begins Research On COVID-19 Remedy –VC Babcock Is Glo, Says Registrar As Glo/Huawei Empowerment Scheme… In another development, 54 four Medical graduates of the university are set for induction as the Benjamin Carson College of Health and Medical Sciences prepares for the 6th Induction. College Provost, Prof. Barnabas Mandong who shared this information also used the platform to shed light on the School’s purpose and mission. He said, “The patient needs compassion, care and competence. Our Medical graduates are trained to be missionaries, not mercenaries; to see the patient as God’s creation that needs care.” Prof. Mandong added that since its inception in 2010, the College has graduated 248 medical doctors who are spread across the globe. “The School of Medicine was established to complement the Federal Government’s efforts and to meet global needs of healthcare. POLL Dean of the School of Clinical Sciences, Dr. James Renner added, “Besides medical training, we also offer healthcare in Neurology, Nephrology and other cardiovascular diseases to reverse the trend of medical tourism.”